Considering that the end of this forecast question is very close and that stock shocks in the next 24 hours are extremely unlikely, I update my previous forecast from 95% to a 100% chance, meaning that I am absolutely confident that the closing value for the pound against the euro on 1 April 2019 will be More than €1.10 but less than €1.20.
Update: current value 1.16. Given the turbulences already endured, it seems impossible that an event will move the pound outside the 1.1-1.2 parameters in the next 24 hours.

Given the ranges here there is virtually 0% chance of the £ will leave the €1.10 to €1.20 range by close of trading on 1 April. However, the pound will continue it's downturn, likely on at accelerating rate. My prediction: 1 April: €1.13 ± 0.02 15 April: €1.11 ± 0.03

(Disclaimer: This question is connected to a Brexit at the 29th of March 2019 and its impact on the currencies. The agreed extension of Brexit beyond 29th contradicts with the underlying assumed scenario. Projecting this question on a new Brexit date wouldn’t make sense regarding the aggregation mechanic of this platform).

As of March 31, the exchange rate of the British Pound to the Euro is 1,16. While there has been some fluctuations during the past months (though the closing value never went below the 1.10 limit, the rate has remained stable during the entire month of March, showing only minor variations. This can be taken as a baserate. (https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/cx250jmk4e7t/pound-sterling-gbp). The House of Commons rejected Theresa May's withdrawal agreement three times, yet this did not affect the rate. Neither did the ecision to extend the deadline for the Uk leaving the EU for that matter. The prime minister's embattled position and the rumours about a revolt in her cabinet failed to have any noticeable effect on the rate as well. Given the political magnitude and far reaching ramifications of these events the chances for the Pound to fall below the 1.10 line in the few remaining hours until April 1 can be considered close to non-existent. Similarly, there is no reason to expect any considerable increase, since the political crisis remains unresolved.

Update: After the rejection of May's withdrawal agreement, for the UK there will be plenty of new possible scenarios developing in the nex weeks, from an hard brexit, to a soft one to a new referendum. In spite of the confusion perceived because of the lack of a clear prospectives of how to act by the Parliament, there hasn't been yet a concrete effective decision (everything is still possible). Also, today the exchange rate is 1,16: I'm confident that this event would not change it over 1.20 or less than 1.10.

I think you may have overlooked one crucial fact. This question resolves 1 April. Given the pounds current stability it is very unlikely to leave the €1.15 ± 0.02 range in the remaining 10 hours. I am predicting a continuing downturn through 14 April, possibly below €1.10. Your prediction seems to aim at 1 January 2020. My prediction for that date is €1.15 ± 0.07. The wide range of Brexit deals including No Deal or accidental crash out by underestimating the flexibility of EU leadership in granting extensions, through remaining in the free-trade zone creates uncertainty that until resolved indicates the pound is likely to remain flat or gradually decline, likely within the €1.10 to €1.15 range. I hope and pray your optimistic long term forecast is accurate.

Update. Now that the uncertainty surrounding Brexit has been resolved, there shouldn't be any politically induced fluctuations within the next 48 hours. The exchange rate has sat consistently between 1.1 and 1.2 for a while now.

Update: On March 29, 2019, MPs rejected Theresa May's EU withdrawal agreement, meaning the UK missed an EU Deadline, which gave the country the chance to delay Brexit until 22nd of May and leave with a deal. Since the value of pound is still 1,16 against the Euro and such kind of political event wasn't capable of causing fluctuation, we can assume that there won't be any dramatic changes on the 1st of April as well.

At the time of writing the pound to euro value is 1.16 according to Bloomberg. They also reports the value being between 1.09 - 1.18 for the past 52 weeks. So I expect very large fluctuations to be unlikely giving below 1.00 and more than 1.30 2% probability each. The value reflects underlying demand and it has been rather stable in the past year in spite of all the Brexit uncertainty. Since the UK has been given an extension until April 12th even without an agreement today, I forecast that the value will remain rather stable until at least April 1st. Currency values are not only determined by political events and this causes irreducible uncertainty regarding the value. For this reason I have put 10% probability in both the 1.00-1.10 and 1.20-1.30 bracket.

As of March 28, the British pound is trading at 1,16 Euros. Hence, the number represents the baseline for the forecast. As the worst exchange rate was 1.1004 on August, 28, 2018, we shouldn't expect dramatic change within 3 days and it going below €1.00. Besides, the uncertainty around the "no-deal" alternative hasn't caused an extreme instability of the currency during the last several months and the exchange rate has been fluctuating between 1.1031-1.1764 since September 2018, being somewhat stable between 1.330-1764 since mid-February of 2019. Furthermore, since the EU has granted article 50 an extension until the 12th of April at least, there is high likelihood of the exchange rate to be between €1.10-1.20 on April 1, 2019.

The implications of political decisions on currency exchange rates are empirically evident. One famose example is the decision of the US to invade Iraq in 2003. Immediately after the decision's announcement, the US Dollar lost 14% against the Euro. (https://moneytransfercomparison.com/major-economical-events-which-impacted-currency-rates/) Turning to Brexit and the question of an appropriate baseline in order to estimate the closing value of the Pound against the Euro on April, 1, it gets complicated due to the fact that the UK is the first country to leave the EU, the world's biggest and most intertwined economic trade block. However, due to the fact that the Brexit process has been going on for quite a while now with several major incidents, such as the decision of the referendum itself, a lost general election for the British prime minister Theresa May, or the rejection of May's deal in the parliament (twice), it makes sense to take a look at the development of the exchange rates throughout this period:
A resolution that’s bullish enough to push the pound that high doesn’t seems possible this week. Uncertainty is likely to continue and that will likely keep the pound range bound.

Today, 21st March 2019, 1£ = 1.15€ In 2016, before the Brexit referendum, the exchange rate was around 1 pound = 1.25/1.3 €; while on 26th of June 2016 (3 days after the Brexit) the value of the pound fell drastically from 1.31 to 1.2. For the rest of 2016 it remains between 1.1 and 1.2. In 2017 the exchange rate has reached a minimum level of 1.075 and a maximum of 1,1955€. In 2018 there wasn’t a huge difference: the average of the exchange rate has been 1£ = 1.1303€, with a maximum of 1.1578 and a minimum of 1.1004 (but always >1.1€). Since the beginning of the 2019 the value of 1 £ has changed between 1,1€ and 1,18€, without ever reaching 1,2€. So, from the statistics, we should exclude the possibility of an exchange rate under 1€, focusing on the other possibilities. The last three months have been a critical period for Great Britain, with the Parliament rejecting twice the agreement reached between the premier May and the EU about a soft Brexit, plus the pressures of the ultimate date to take a decision (29 of March) and the internal fights in the party at the government. All these factors have an impact on the markets, but in the last years they have never had an effect that brought to have an exchange rate higher than 1.2 (excluded). Also, one week ago the British Parliament has approved the delay of the Brexit until the 30th of June, which could make the market stable until that day, because there won’t be yet an official Brexit. Still, I’m sure the pound will remain weak but sticking between 1.10 and 1.20€. However, because the markets are unpredictable, we cannot exclude completely the possibility of a higher loss for the GBP. Also, the EU has still to accept or not the extension of the art.50 (hard Brexit is still theoretically possible). These reasons make me set some possibilities for the first and the second options.

In the last year, the Pound Sterling (GBP) has fluctuated between a low of 1.1028 and a high of 1.173 against the Euro. The GBP seems to respond to Brexit developments. Uncertainty has correlated with a decline in value, and the opposite is true when the future appears to be more stable. For example, the aforementioned high was reached on March 14, 2019 — the day in which the Commons voted to allow May to request permission to extend — in response to increased knowledge of the state of the market in the near future (one where the UK is unlikely to leave the EU on March 29). On April 1, whether an extension has been granted will be known. So too, will the length of that extension if granted. This is likely to stabilise the market — no matter the outcome, since the market prefers to operate in the known. It is unforeseeable that the GBP will reach a value outside the 1.1-1.2 parameter, as it has not done in the last year and the greater certainty surrounding Brexit on April should reduce major anomalies. Thus this is forecasted at 80%. An equal chance of 10% is given to either side of this parameter accounting for the chance a boom resulting from a stabilisation, or a serious fall resulting from an unexpected hard Brexit.

GBP price against the Euro on March 19, 2019: 1.17 GBP = 1 euro More uncertainty = a weaker currency than other currencies Indeed, on 27 June 2016 after the vote in favor of a UK exit from the EU, the pound fell to 83.26 pence for one euro, a bad presage. Since November 2015, the pound fell sharply from 1.43 for 1 euro on November 27, 2015, to 1.17 on November 25, 2016, after the vote. Since 2016, the pound has stagnated around 1.15 on average until now. It is therefore in a low position, and the great uncertainty that the Brexit will bring by April 1, 2019 will not tend to increase certainly. It must therefore be known that the British political evolution will be inseparably linked to the evolution of the pound, and that Brexit will therefore be the catalyst of the value of the pound. According to the different scenarios of Brexit, we can try to understand the possible value of pound against the euro : - In the case of the extension of the Brexit deadline, the value of the pound will not have to change so much and therefore be between 1.10 and 1.20. Or even in the case of a finely played Brexit soft, go up a little more than the average of the last two years. Moreover, this Brexit scenario seems the most likely (in a forecast I place it at 65%). - In the case of Parliament's adoption of the Brexit agreement, the pound is expected to fall but still stabilize thanks to agreements with the European Union. The likelihood of this scenario is 20% in my opinion. The fall will not be too brutal. In case of No-Deal, depreciation of the currency will be extremely strong. Indeed, imports will be much cheaper against UK exports, which will be taxed by the EU. In this case, the scenario for the pound is not impossible to be below the 1.0 value bar. Nevertheless, the likelihood of this scenario at present is 10%. It is therefore more likely, following the current Brexit events, that the pound will be between 1.10 and 1.20 for 1.0 euro on 1 April 2019. However, the great uncertainty of this event does not exclude in any case an average decline in the price, or a very sharp drop in case of No-Deal, which is not out of the odds, even if it is less possible.

My forecast takes its move from a set of considerations. First, cutting the extremes. For the pound to fall below 1 euro or rising above 1,3 is absolutely unlikely. Even though the possible enter into effect of the Brexit could have a major impact on pund's value, these two extreme cases are, in my opinion, almost impossible. The other considerations necessarlly have to take into account the major economic and politic dynamics that can happen in the next month in Europe and UK - namely, most of all the path the Brexit will take. While in this forecast I won't analyze in lenght all the possibilities, here I reduce the analysis to economic matters - not exactely my field, but it's worth a shot. The resilience of the pound, even in the most turbolent phases of UK politics since 2017, is definetly something to take into account. UK is and will remain a big economy, which in my opinion will be affected by the turbolence deriving from Brexit but not necessarily in a catastrophic way. Moreover, a macroeconomic dynamic has to be taken into account: while the effects of the Brexit could lower the pound's value, the expenses deriving from the deal - if the deal remains the one stipulated, which is debatable, the UK will have to pay around 36 billions to the EU - will produce a reduction in the availabilty of pounds on the currency market, which in macroeconomics means an increase in the pound's value. If the UK's export, on the other side, will suffer for the exit from the EU, this would lead to a decrease in the pound's value to compensate the exports' reduction. All in all, wether the Brexit will be delayed (which would lead to a more or less stability in the exchange rate) or the Brexit will happen the 29th of this month the pound will be stable. In the even of a no deal, the pound could depreciate slightly (20% to the second option)

When learning the mechanics of GJ Open, I made a practice prediction on the UK rate to the Euro. Since then, I have decided to reevaluate my previous prediction and use those judgements as a baseline for using Bayes Theorem. First, the below 1 Euro and above 1.30 Euro I gave a 0% chance, so neither will be used as Bayesian mathematics doesn’t change already existing 0% or 100% predictions. First, I gave a 10% chance of the Pound being above 1.20 Euro. I made this based on the assumption that the UK pulled off Brexit successfully (which is my conditional). Currently, GJ Open says that there is a 26% chance of this happening. When Bayes Theorem is applied, it now gives a 3.76% chance. Since I applied the possibility of a false conditional to both by 1-1.10 Euro percentage and 1.10-1.20 Euro percentage, I then proportionally redistributed the reduced chance of ending above 1.20 to these other categories.

We are in very unpredictable times and I have minimal skill. In general, expertise performs badly in these situations too. The first question I need to answer is: will any amount of research I can do allow me to out perform the market. Although I don't agree that markets are perfectly efficient they are closer to a random walk than a predictable trend. If "the crowd" believed that Euros would be more valuable on 1st of April than today anyone with spare money or who could borrow it should buy Euros today, the demand would go up leading to price going up, until the price is marginally lower than the expected price on that day. The fact that the price of a Euro now is 86p suggests that the best guess as to the price of euros on 1st April is 86p. I have allowed for wide variation in price given the unlikeness of anyone government to intervene to a heroic degree to interfere with market forces.
